<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="50" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d50">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Inquiry files</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Dr. <persName corresp="#p_BI1" type="from">Isaiah
                                    Bowman</persName> to Dr. <persName corresp="#p_MSE1" type="to">S. E. Mezes</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                                </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-13">July 13,
                                    1918</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Dr. <persName corresp="#p_MSE1">Mezes</persName></hi>: May I observe, in all respect, that the
                            state of affairs you point out in the attached memorandum<note n="19" xml:id="d50fn19">Dr. <persName corresp="#p_MSE1">Mezes</persName>’
                                memorandum of July 9, 1918, <ref target="#pg_99">p. 99</ref>.</note>
                            is due to the <pb facs="0173" n="103" xml:id="pg_103"/> present loose
                            organization of the Inquiry—possibly an excellent thing in a small
                            democratic organization but wholly inappropriate to a large one now
                            establishing broad relationships with almost every scientific bureau of
                            the government.</p>
                        <p>The time has come when there should be a stricter division of functions
                            among the officers of the Inquiry and an exact definition of status and
                            appointments. It is a source of growing embarrassment to remain as we
                            are.</p>
                        <p>Forgive my very direct and even blunt presentation of this matter. It
                            saves time and it is the way I like to speak.</p>
                        <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BI1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Isaiah Bowman</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>